    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv in the current directory. For each file, return a compact summary with: 1) total row count; 2) number of unique cmdb_id; 3) list of unique cmdb_id (limit to first 50 entries); 4) list of unique KPI/trace/log names (for metric -> kpi_name, trace -> trace_name, log -> log_name) (limit to first 50); 5) minimum and maximum timestamp values; 6) the top 20 rows of the file. Return the results in a concise JSON-like or tabular text form for each file. Do not perform any thresholding or filtering yet."
}

{
    "analysis": "The Executor computed global percentiles (P95 and P5) per component-KPI for metric, trace, and log series across the full available data, and returned compact group summaries limited to top groups by count_in_window. Key observations: metric data spans 09:30–10:30 and many adservice KPIs show full coverage (61 points) with 31 points in the incident window; trace and log groups cover the 10:00–10:30 window. error_logs.csv is empty. With global thresholds available, the next step is metric-based anomaly detection inside the incident window (2022-03-21 10:00:00 to 2022-03-21 10:30:00 UTC+8) to narrow candidate faulty components. We should look for both high-side anomalies (value >= P95) and low-side anomalies (value <= P5) because traffic/business KPIs can drop during network failures. The goal of the next query is to rank component-KPIs by anomaly counts in the window and show earliest anomaly times and severity to pick top candidates for further fault identification and trace/log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the previously computed per-(cmdb_id, kpi_name) global P95 and P5 (stored in kernel variables), scan metric.csv rows within the incident window 2022-03-21 10:00:00 to 2022-03-21 10:30:00 (UTC+8) and mark a row as anomalous if value >= P95 OR value <= P5. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) group compute: anomaly_count (number of anomalous rows in window), total_points_in_window, p95, p5, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (the smallest timestamp among anomalies), max_value (max value in window), min_value (min value in window), max_violation_ratio defined as max(abs(value - threshold)/max(threshold, 1e-9)) across anomalous rows where threshold is p95 for high-side anomalies and p5 for low-side anomalies. Return the top 20 groups sorted by anomaly_count descending. For each returned group include: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95, p5, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_violation_ratio, and up to the first 5 anomalous timestamps for that group. Keep output compact (one aggregated row per group)."
}

{
    "analysis": "Executor flagged many persistent anomalies across the entire 10:00–10:30 window. Top anomalous groups include container.memory-failure and container CPU throttling/fs_read metrics on specific pods (e.g., frontend-2, productcatalogservice-0, cartservice-0/1/2), and several node-level I/O and zombie process metrics. Many global P95/P5 values for these KPIs are 0.0, so all non-zero readings in the window are marked anomalous; these anomalies are persistent (anomaly_count == total_points_in_window), with earliest anomalies at 2022-03-21 10:00:00. From this we can infer there are sustained resource-related signals across multiple containers and nodes starting at the beginning of the window, but we still need to (1) identify true faults as consecutive anomalous subseries (filter noise), (2) quantify severity per fault (max violation ratio within the fault), and (3) use traces/logs to determine which faulty component is the most likely root cause. The next step is therefore to extract consecutive anomaly segments (faults) for the top anomalous groups (bounded set) and summarize each fault's start time, end time, duration, and severity so we can compare components and pick candidates for trace/log correlation.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the anomaly scan results stored in the kernel, select the top 12 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) groups by anomaly_count. For each selected group, scan metric rows inside the window 2022-03-21 10:00:00 to 2022-03-21 10:30:00 (UTC+8) and identify consecutive anomalous segments where anomaly flag is True for contiguous minutes. For each group return a compact list (limit to first 5 faults per group) with these fields: cmdb_id, kpi_name, fault_index (1..), fault_start_timestamp, fault_end_timestamp, fault_length_minutes, fault_max_value, fault_min_value, fault_max_violation_ratio (max across points in this fault as previously defined). Also return per-group summary: total_faults_found, earliest_fault_start. Sort groups by earliest_fault_start then by fault_max_violation_ratio descending. Keep output to at most 12 groups and at most 5 faults per group." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We segmented metric anomalies and found many persistent, full-window faults (10:00→10:30) across multiple containers and nodes. The top flagged KPIs are container memory_failures, container CPU throttling, container fs_reads, and node I/O/zombie processes. Many global P95/P5 baselines are zero, so severity ratios are inflated; nonetheless these faults are persistent and simultaneous across pods/nodes starting at 10:00. To localize the single root cause component we must now use trace data to determine which service/container in the call chains was actually impacted (the root cause is typically the last downstream faulty container/service in traces). Therefore we need a compact trace-level anomaly scan within the incident window to find which trace series (duration_p95/duration_mean/error_rate/row_count) show abnormal behavior (high latency, increased error_rate, or drops in row_count) and their earliest anomaly times. This will narrow candidate services/containers for downstream correlation with the metric faults.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the trace-level global P95/P5 values previously computed and the trace.csv data stored in kernel variables, scan rows inside the window 2022-03-21 10:00:00 to 2022-03-21 10:30:00 (UTC+8). Flag a row as anomalous if value >= P95 OR value <= P5. Aggregate by (cmdb_id, trace_name) and compute: total_points_in_window, anomaly_count, p95, p5, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (min timestamp among anomalies), latest_anomaly_timestamp, and provide up to 5 sample anomalous (timestamp, value) pairs per group. Return the top 20 groups sorted by anomaly_count desc, then by earliest_anomaly_timestamp asc. Include only the fields: cmdb_id, trace_name, p95, p5, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, latest_anomaly_timestamp, sample_anomalies (up to 5). Keep output compact (one row per group)."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous steps summarized: global P95/P5 thresholds were computed for all component-KPIs. Metric-level anomaly detection inside the incident window (2022-03-21 10:00–10:30 UTC+8) found many persistent, full-window anomalies across multiple containers (frontend-2, frontend-1, productcatalogservice-0, cartservice-0/1/2, currencyservice2-0, cartservice2-0, etc.) and several node-level KPIs (node-1, node-2, node-4, node-6). Many of these KPI baselines (P95/P5) are 0.0, which means any non-zero readings were flagged and produced inflated violation ratios. Fault segmentation showed most of these groups have one continuous fault spanning the entire window with earliest fault start at 10:00 UTC+8. Trace-level anomaly scanning also reported persistent anomalies, concentrated in adservice-* and cartservice-* traces (error_rate and duration-related traces) across the same window. What we can derive so far: an infrastructure-level signal (memory_failures, CPU throttling, fs reads, node I/O) appears simultaneously across many pods/nodes starting at 10:00; traces show application-level abnormalities in adservice and cartservice. To localize a single root cause component we must correlate metric-faulty containers/pods with trace anomalies to find the most downstream faulty component in call chains (the root cause is normally the last downstream faulty service/container within traces). Therefore the next atomic step is to aggregate trace anomalies by cmdb_id to identify which containers/services have the most distinct anomalous trace series and earliest anomaly times, and to indicate whether these cmdb_id values appear among the metric-faulty component list discovered earlier. This will prioritize candidates for final localization and enable linking the metric faults (resource signals) with service-level symptoms in traces.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the trace anomaly results (and the metric fault segmentation stored in kernel variables), aggregate trace anomalies by cmdb_id for the window 2022-03-21 10:00:00 to 10:30:00 UTC+8. For each cmdb_id compute: 1) total_trace_series_in_window (number of distinct trace_name groups present in the window), 2) anomalous_trace_series_count (count of trace_name groups with >=1 anomaly), 3) earliest_anomaly_timestamp (min timestamp across its anomalous trace rows), 4) latest_anomaly_timestamp (max timestamp across its anomalous trace rows), 5) sample_trace_names_with_anomalies (up to 10 trace_name values), and 6) in_metric_faults flag (True if this cmdb_id appears in the top metric-faulty component list from the previous step). Return the top 20 cmdb_id rows sorted by anomalous_trace_series_count desc then earliest_anomaly_timestamp asc. Include fields: cmdb_id, anomalous_trace_series_count, total_trace_series_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, latest_anomaly_timestamp, sample_trace_names_with_anomalies, in_metric_faults. Keep the output compact (one row per cmdb_id)." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed: 1) global thresholds (P95/P5) per component-KPI computed on full series; 2) metric-level anomaly detection and fault segmentation inside the incident window (2022-03-21 10:00–10:30 UTC+8), which discovered many persistent, full-window faults across multiple pods and nodes (notably container memory_failures, CPU throttling, fs_reads, and node I/O/zombie counts) that all begin at 10:00; 3) trace-level anomaly detection and aggregation by cmdb_id, which shows widespread persistent trace anomalies across many services, and a clear overlap between metric-faulty components and trace anomalies for these cmdb_ids: frontend-1, frontend-2, productcatalogservice-0, cartservice-0, cartservice-1, cartservice-2. From these results we can infer a correlated problem that started at 2022-03-21 10:00:00 and affected many pods and nodes. However, we have not yet used logs to disambiguate the underlying resource-level reason (e.g., memory failure vs CPU throttling vs node disk I/O), nor have we located the single most downstream faulty component in traces that would identify the root cause component. Next, we should use log.csv (and the previously computed P95/P5 for log metrics) to check for log-level anomalies for the prioritized candidate cmdb_ids to determine whether any container-level resource faults (e.g., memory failures, OOMs, error_count spikes) are evidenced in logs that would indicate the underlying reason and exact root cause time.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the existing kernel variables (global P95/P5 for log groups and the loaded log.csv), analyze log data within the incident window 2022-03-21 10:00:00 to 2022-03-21 10:30:00 UTC+8 for the candidate cmdb_ids: [\"frontend-1\",\"frontend-2\",\"productcatalogservice-0\",\"cartservice-0\",\"cartservice-1\",\"cartservice-2\"]. For each candidate cmdb_id do the following: \n1) Group by (cmdb_id, log_name) and compute per-group: total_points_in_window, p95, p5, anomaly_count (rows with value >= p95 OR <= p5), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (min timestamp among anomalies). \n2) For the cmdb_id produce a compact summary row with: cmdb_id, total_log_series_in_window (number of distinct log_name in window), anomalous_log_series_count (count of groups with anomaly_count>0), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_across_logs, and a sample_anomalous_rows list (up to 10 entries) showing (timestamp, log_name, value) for anomalous rows. \n3) Additionally flag whether any log.error_count > 0 appears in the window for that cmdb_id and the first timestamp when log.error_count > 0 occurred. \nReturn at most one summary row per candidate (so up to 6 rows). Keep outputs compact and textual (one row per candidate) and rely on the previously computed global P95/P5 (do NOT recompute thresholds using filtered window data)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed global threshold calculation, metric anomaly detection, fault segmentation, trace anomaly scanning, and targeted log analysis for prioritized candidates. Recap of what the Executor's outputs show: \n- Many metric KPIs show persistent faults spanning the full 10:00–10:30 window. Top metric signals are container.memory_failures, container CPU throttling, container fs_reads, and node I/O/zombie counts. Many of these faults begin at 2022-03-21 10:00:00 UTC+8. \n- Trace anomalies are widespread across services; components that are both metric-faulty and trace-faulty include frontend-1, frontend-2, productcatalogservice-0, cartservice-0, cartservice-1, cartservice-2. \n- Log checks for those six candidates show no non-zero log.error_count (no explicit application errors), but log.row_count shows some anomalous points; log.error_count thresholds of 0.0 produced misleading anomaly flags. \nWhat remains to determine the single root cause: we must (1) decide the fault level (node vs container vs service) and (2) among multiple faulty containers identify the most-likely root cause component using trace call-direction (downstream-ness) and relative severity. From earlier severity metrics, container-level memory_failures produced the largest deviation ratios, so the root cause level is likely a container. Now we need to find which of the candidate faulty containers is the most downstream faulty component in service call chains. To do that, we should inspect trace_name patterns for each candidate to see whether that candidate appears primarily as a callee (incoming traces, e.g., trace.from_<other_service>) or as a caller (outgoing traces, e.g., trace.to_<other_service>) or only self traces. The most downstream faulty container will show many 'trace.from_*' series (requests arriving to it) and few or no 'trace.to_*' series calling other services.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For the candidate cmdb_ids [\"frontend-1\",\"frontend-2\",\"productcatalogservice-0\",\"cartservice-0\",\"cartservice-1\",\"cartservice-2\"]: scan trace.csv inside the window 2022-03-21 10:00:00 to 2022-03-21 10:30:00 (UTC+8). For each cmdb_id compute and return one compact row with these fields: cmdb_id, total_distinct_trace_names_in_window, count_trace_from_* (number of distinct trace_name values containing 'trace.from_'), count_trace_to_* (number of distinct trace_name values containing 'trace.to_'), count_trace_self_* (number containing 'trace.self'), sample_from_services (extract unique service tokens from 'trace.from_<service>' patterns, up to 10), sample_to_services (extract unique service tokens from 'trace.to_<service>' patterns, up to 10), earliest_trace_timestamp_in_window. Keep output to one row per candidate (6 rows)."
}

